Hi everyone,
in a ASP.NET Core for .NET 5 application, suppose we have a very basic `AuthorizationHandler` like this one.
```csharp
public class CustomRequirementAuthorizationHandler : AuthorizationHandler<CustomRequirement>
{
  protected override Task HandleRequirementAsync(AuthorizationHandlerContext context, CustomRequirement requirement)
  {
    // This gets called twice
    // First time with a context.Resource of type Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.DefaultHttpContext
    // Second time with a context.Resource of type Microsoft.AspNetCore.Mvc.Infrastructure.ResourceInvoker.AuthorizationFilterContextSealed
    context.Succeed(requirement);
    return Task.CompletedTask;
  }
}
```

Its `HandleRequirementAsync` method gets executed twice if I also add a global `AuthorizeFilter` like so:
```csharp
public void ConfigureServices(IServiceCollection services)
{
    services.AddControllers(config =>
    {
        var policy = new AuthorizationPolicyBuilder().RequireAssertion(context => true).Build();
        config.Filters.Add(new AuthorizeFilter(policy));
    });

    services.AddAuthorization(options =>
    {
        options.AddPolicy("MyPolicy", builder =>
        {
            builder.AddRequirements(new CustomRequirement());
        });
    });
    services.AddSingleton<IAuthorizationHandler, CustomRequirementAuthorizationHandler>();
}
```
The policy is applied to an MVC action like so:
```csharp
public class HomeController : Controller
{
  [Authorize(Policy = "MyPolicy")]
  public IActionResult Index()
  {
    return Content("Ok");
  }
}
```

A repro is here
https://github.com/BrightSoul/AuthorizationHandlerMultipleInvocations

I'm not sure if this is intended behavior or not but it seems somewhat strange that the same logic gets executed twice within the scope of the same HTTP request. This could lead to reduced performance when executing time expensive operations in the `HandleRequirementAsync` method (e.g. database access).

